    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2320568120" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2320568120" />
    <a title="Chrissie" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/632247-chrissie"><img alt="Chrissie" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1321799585p2/632247.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2320568120?book_show_action=true">Mar 24, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Chrissie" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Chrissie" href="/user/show/632247-chrissie">Chrissie</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/632247-chrissie?shelf=usa">usa</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/632247-chrissie?shelf=2018-read">2018-read</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/632247-chrissie?shelf=audible-uk">audible-uk</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/632247-chrissie?shelf=bio">bio</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2320568120" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer17861629710283520111">Please start by reading the GR book description here: <a target='_blank' rel='noopener nofollow' href='https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/25852784-evicted?utm_content=review_cta_book_image&amp;utm_medium=email&amp;utm_source=bookend'>https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/2...</a><br/><br/>The book addresses the need for affordable housing, a crucial problem in America today. By looking at two landlords and eight families, statistics become personal. They gain meaning.<br/><br/> The first third of the book did however give me trouble. The so-called “families” are distended making it hard to get a grip on them. Their stories are not related one by one, but all mixed together which leads to confusion</span>
  <span id="freeText17861629710283520111" style="display:none">Please start by reading the GR book description here: <a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/25852784-evicted?utm_content=review_cta_book_image&amp;utm_medium=email&amp;utm_source=bookend">https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/2...</a><br /><br />The book addresses the need for affordable housing, a crucial problem in America today. By looking at two landlords and eight families, statistics become personal. They gain meaning.<br /><br /> The first third of the book did however give me trouble. The so-called “families” are distended making it hard to get a grip on them. Their stories are not related one by one, but all mixed together which leads to confusion. I did not feel for these individuals nor their plight. I empathized with none of them, in fact they annoyed me. All of them had been dealt a bad hand in the card game of life, but they could not possibly be viewed as guiltless innocents either. They had made seriously poor choices. I found myself asking repeatedly what it is that makes one person fight obstacles and preserve their dignity while another succumbs. This is an interesting question, but not what the book is about.<br /><br />Then something clicked, and I don’t quite know why. These people became not just a mixed jumble of individuals but clear identities each with their own background, concerns and personal endeavors. The fog cleared, and I could relate to them. I had been seriously considering dumping the book. Don’t do that, be patient, the fog does clear.<br /><br />The book gets you into the lives of real people and this is of great value. Numbers one cannot relate too, people you can. The book follows up the fate of each and every one touched upon. By the book’s end you care, and you do want to know!<br /><br />The book concludes with a fantastic epilog. It draws conclusions and gives guidelines for changes that need to be made. It explains in detail how the study was conducted, giving the reader total confidence in the information provided. <br /><br />The book does not merely draw a problem. It goes a step further suggesting how improvement and change can be made.<br /><br />The audiobook is narrated by Dion Graham. It is easy to follow, but his pacing tells the reader how we are to view the facts. I prefer a more neutral presentation. Many would not agree with me. I have given the narration three stars.</span>
  <a data-text-id="17861629710283520111" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

